%I A395145 #17 Apr 21 2026 00:33:51
%S A395145 1,2,4,8,16,32,64,128,258,516,1038
%N A395145 Maximum number of ISO A(n) sheets that fit orthogonally without overlap into a single ISO A0 sheet.
%C A395145 As ISO 216 only defines A0 to A10, this sequence is complete. The values starting from n=8 deviate from powers of two (2^n) because ISO A(n) is defined in rounded whole millimeter, enabling more to fit than without rounding.
%H A395145 N. Friedrich, <a href="https://github.com/noel-friedrich/paper-packing/">Table of how many ISO A(i) fit into a single ISO A(j) for i>=j and 0<=i,j<=10</a>.
%H A395145 N. Friedrich, <a href="https://www.noel-friedrich.de/uploads/paper-packing.pdf">1038 A10s fit into one A0</a>, FUN 2026.
%H A395145 N. Friedrich, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zDKBCIMkDbw&amp;t=129s">YouTube video outlining the problem and proof ideas</a>.
%e A395145 For n=1, two sheets of ISO A1 can be fitted into a single ISO A0.
%e A395145 For n=9, only 516 sheets can be fitted in, even though ~519.72 could fit in by area alone.
%K A395145 nonn,fini,full,dumb,new
%O A395145 0,2
%A A395145 _Noel Friedrich_, Apr 14 2026
